{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/apache-spark-a-conceptual-orientation-e326f8c57a64", "time": 1683000696.572209, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/apache-spark-a-conceptual-orientation-e326f8c57a64/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Apache Spark: A Conceptual Orientation | by Alexander Shropshire | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Apache Spark: A Conceptual Orientation", "description": "Apache Spark, once part of the Hadoop ecosystem, is a powerful open-source, general-purpose distributed data-processing engine that provides real-time stream processing, interactive processing, graph\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://spark.apache.org/", "anchor_text": "Apache Spark", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "http://hadoop.apache.org/", "anchor_text": "Hadoop", "paragraph_index": 0}], "all_paragraphs": ["Apache Spark, once part of the Hadoop ecosystem, is a powerful open-source, general-purpose distributed data-processing engine that provides real-time stream processing, interactive processing, graph processing, in-memory processing, batch processing with very fast speed, and ease of use. Application developers and data scientists incorporate Spark into their applications to rapidly query, analyze, and transform data at scale. Tasks most frequently associated with Spark include ETL and SQL batch jobs across large data sets, processing of streaming data from sensors, IoT, or financial systems, and machine learning tasks. Leading tech companies now desire a powerful engine that can do all of these things, and luckily, Spark is not too difficult to learn if you already know Python and SQL.", "Originally developed at UC Berkeley in 2009, many internet juggernauts have since adopted Spark to collectively process petabytes of data on clusters of 8K+ nodes. It\u2019s become the largest open source community in big data, with over 1K+ code contributors, 180K+ members, and 400+ meetups.", "Before Spark, Google used MapReduce (framework white paper published in 2004), a resilient distributed processing framework made to index the large volume of web content across large clusters of commodity servers. They wanted to distribute data: split a data file into chunks called data blocks that could be distributed across many nodes and replicated across the cluster. They wanted to distribute computational power to automatically parallelize and execute tasks on a large cluster of commodity machines each working on a data subset. They wanted both to the data and the computation to handle failure well by deferring faults to another node.", "A year later (2005), Apache Hadoop was created \u2014 an open-source framework designed for distributed storage and processing of very large data sets across clusters of computers. This framework supported the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), the bottom layer component for storage which breaks up files into chunks and distributes them across cluster nodes. It supported Yarn for job scheduling and cluster resource management, and MapReduce for parallel processing, among others.", "In 2009, the AMP Lab at UC Berkeley began initial work on Apache Spark. In 2013\u20132014, the Apache Software Foundation decided to make Spark a top priority, alongside wealthy backers like Databricks, IBM, and Huawei. The goal was to make a sort of better version of MapReduce. Spark executes much faster by caching data in memory across multiple parallel operations, whereas MapReduce involves more reading and writing from disk. Spark has faster startup, better parallelism, and better CPU utilization. It provides a richer functional programming model than MapReduce and supports iterative algorithms.", "Spark is capable of handling several petabytes of data at a time. It\u2019s flexible, with an extensive set of developer libraries and APIs across Java, Python, R, and Scala. Spark is often used with distributed data stores such as MapR XD, Hadoop\u2019s HDFS, and Amazon\u2019s S3, with popular NoSQL databases such as MapR Database, Apache HBase, Apache Cassandra, and MongoDB, and with distributed messaging stores such as MapR Event Store and Apache Kafka.", "Let\u2019s connect! I encourage you to comment, share, or message me directly with your thoughts on the ideas presented here, or suggestions on interesting topics I should look into going forward.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Finance x Data @ Brex | Past: Legendary Entertainment, VEVO, AOL | Let\u2019s Connect!"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fe326f8c57a64&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fapache-spark-a-conceptual-orientation-e326f8c57a64&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fapache-spark-a-conceptual-orientation-e326f8c57a64&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fapache-spark-a-conceptual-orientation-e326f8c57a64&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav---------------------